## Issues to fix

1. REMOVE the research question line that says 'or Pi agents on the symbient substrate'. This is purely WibWob-DOS IPC. No substrate, no control.ts, no Pi RPC. Scrub any remaining substrate/control.ts references if they exist.

2. The Simple Description is good but add: 'The human's messages appear in all instances too — not just the AI responses.'

3. The relay prefix format '[ww-relay] id=... from=... role=... | ...' is ugly and will confuse the AI receiving it. The AI will see a machine-formatted string and try to parse it or comment on it. Simplify to something natural like '[Instance 1 says]: actual message content'. The dedup should use a side-channel (the event_id tracking set), not an in-band text marker. The is_relay_message() check should look at the delivered_to_target set, not parse content text.

4. BUT WAIT — there's a fundamental problem. When the broker sends via wibwob_ask, it appears as a USER message in the target instance. The target AI responds to it. That response gets picked up by the broker and relayed to the original instance as ANOTHER user message. The original AI responds. Loop. The [ww-relay] prefix WAS the loop-breaker but I just told you to remove it. Think about this carefully and propose a clean solution. Maybe: broker tracks message content hashes per instance, and if a message was SENT to an instance by the broker, it ignores that same message when it appears in that instance's history. The broker already has delivered_to_target — use that properly.

5. Actually — think even harder. When broker sends 'hello from instance 1' to instance 2 via wibwob_ask, instance 2's chat shows it as a user message AND triggers an AI response. The AI response is genuine new content. The broker SHOULD relay that back to instance 1. But instance 1 will also generate a response to it. And so on. This IS the group chat working as intended — the loop IS the conversation. The only thing that should stop it is max-turns and cooldown. The dedup problem is narrower: don't relay a message that the broker itself injected (because it would just be a copy). So: when broker sends X to instance 2, record the EXACT text that was sent. When polling instance 2's history, skip any message whose content exactly matches a broker-injected message. That's the dedup.

6. The effort estimate table is good. Keep it.

7. Remove 'Option A only' comments from the Python script docstring. There is no Option B. It's just the script.

